\begin_layout Subsection
Probability Interpretation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Classical light is described by electromagnetic waves (Maxwell's equations)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
e.g.
 E field along the x-axis 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{E}(x)=\underline{E_{0}}\sin(kx-\omega t)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Power of this wave is proportional to the 
\begin_inset Formula $(amplitude)^{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\propto E_{0}^{2}\;(\text{{\textstyle Energy/sec} perpendicular to the beam)}
\]

\end_inset

Quantum mechanics however sees the beam of light as consisting of a finite
 number of particles, discrete photons, with energy
\begin_inset Formula $=\hbar\omega$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Rightarrow Power\propto n\hbar\omega
\]

\end_inset

where n=number of particles detected per second.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To allow these two equations to match up and describe the same situation;
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\propto(amplitude)^{2}\text{of wavefunction describing photons}
\]

\end_inset

This must also apply in quantum mechanics when n becomes very small, i.e.
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ll1$
\end_inset

, when the photons are detected separately.
 So this now works as an average power over a length of time when many photons
 are detected but quantum mechanics cannot predict the arrival of individual
 photons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This invariably leads to a probabilistic interpretation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(amplitude)^{2}\text{of the wave function}\propto\text{probability of a photon arriving per second}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Uncertainty in Quantum Mechanics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A sine wave has a definite momentum, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p=\hbar k=\frac{h}{\lambda}
\]

\end_inset

But the amplitude is the same for all values of x, so there is an equal
 probability of being anywhere in x, i.e.
 no information on the position of the particle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A localized particle can be described with a wave packet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now there is a finite probability of finding the particle in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 but zero elsewhere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here the wave packet has a wave of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 This can be constructed by summing together a large number of sine and
 cosine waves of different wavelengths and amplitudes (Fourier Analysis).
 But now, by limiting the spacial range, some of the information regarding
 the momentum has been lost.
 So as 
\begin_inset Formula $k\rightarrow\bigtriangleup k$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p=\hbar k
\]

\end_inset

Rigorous analysis of this shows that the limit is Heisenberg's Uncertainty
 principle,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigtriangleup x\bigtriangleup p\geq\frac{\hbar}{2}
\]

\end_inset

The intrinsic quantum limit of to the information available arises from
 the wave picture, not dependent on the measurement technique.
\end_layout

