\begin_layout Standard
For a full description of an object with quantum mechanics, we need an equation
 of motion.
 This is analogous to the classical wave equation in 1 dimension,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial^{2}\psi}{\partial x^{2}}=\frac{1}{v^{2}}\frac{\partial^{2}\psi}{\partial t^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

is the classical wave-function.
 If this were describing a light wave, 
\begin_inset Formula $v=c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

would be the equation of the electromagnetic or magnetic field.
 Its a 2nd order differential equation and can be derived from Newton's
 and Maxwell's equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quantum mechanical version however cannot be derived from any more basic
 postulates as it is one of the fundamental postulates in quantum mechanics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Plausibility Argument
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To justify the form of Schrödinger's Equation (SE), it must satisfy a number
 of constraints.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Energy and momentum equations,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
E & = & mc^{2}\nonumber \\
p & = & \hbar k
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Energy conservation at non-relativistic speeds, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
E & = & \frac{p^{2}}{2m}+V\\
\text{Total energy of system} & = & E_{k}+E_{p}\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Differential equation must be linear to allow superposition if 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

are each solutions of SE, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi=a\psi_{1}+b\psi_{2}
\]

\end_inset

 (where a and b are constants) must be another solution.
 This leads to the property of superposition.
 Combine these two,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\hbar^{2}k^{2}}{2m}+V=\hbar\omega
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For a free particle, 
\begin_inset Formula $v=v_{0}=\text{constant},$
\end_inset

 expect a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin+\cos$
\end_inset

 wave solution with no preferred position as all positions are equivalent
 to each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So try free particle solution of the form,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(x,t)=A(\cos(kx-\omega t)+\gamma\sin(kx-\omega t))
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A,\,\gamma=\text{constants}$
\end_inset

 to be determined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Differentiate with respect to time,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial t} & = & A\omega(\sin(kx-\omega t)-\gamma\cos(kx-\omega t))\\
\frac{\partial^{2}\psi}{\partial t^{2}} & = & -Ak(\cos(kx-\omega t)-\gamma\sin(kx-\omega t))
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Comparing (4) and (5) with (3) suggests that the differential equation to
 contain 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{2}\,\omega$
\end_inset

 terms,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\alpha\frac{\partial^{2}\psi}{\partial x^{2}}+V_{0}\psi=\beta\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\,\beta=\text{constants}$
\end_inset

 fixed by equation (3).
 This is very similar to the classical wave equation other than the classical
 wave equation has a 2nd order differential with respect to time where as
 the quantum wave equation has a 1st.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So sub (4), (5) into (6),
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A\left(-\alpha k^{2}+V_{0}\right)(\cos(kx-\omega t)+\gamma\sin(kx-\omega t)=A\beta\omega(\sin(kx-\omega t)-\gamma\cos(kx-\omega t))
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This equation must be true for all values of x and t, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\text{For, }kx-\omega t & = & 0\nonumber \\
\Rightarrow\sin(kx-\omega t) & = & 0\nonumber \\
-\alpha k^{2}+V_{0} & = & -\beta\omega\gamma\\
\text{For, }kx-\omega t & = & \frac{\pi}{2}\nonumber \\
\Rightarrow\cos(kx-\omega t) & = & 0\nonumber \\
\Rightarrow(-\alpha k^{2}+V_{0})\gamma & = & \beta\omega
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Divide (7)/(8)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Rightarrow\frac{1}{\gamma}=-\gamma
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma^{2}=-1,\:\gamma=\sqrt{-1}=\pm i
\]

\end_inset

The sign choice for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is completely arbitrary, by convention 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=+i$
\end_inset

.
 So (4) becomes,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\psi(x,t) & = & A(\cos(kx-\omega t)+i\sin(kx-\omega t))\\
 & = & Ae^{i(kx-\omega t)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This is the equation for a free particle,
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(x,t)=Ae^{i(kx-\omega t)}
\]

\end_inset


\emph default
From (8)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\alpha k^{2}+V_{0}=-i\beta\omega\qquad\because\gamma=i
\]

\end_inset

Match terms with (3)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\hbar^{2}k^{2}}{2m}+V_{0}=\hbar\omega
\]

\end_inset

So for energy conservation 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=i\hbar$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sub into (6)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{-\hbar^{2}}{2m}\frac{\partial^{2}\psi}{\partial x^{2}}+V\psi=i\hbar\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial t}
\]

\end_inset

This is the time dependent form of the Schrödinger Equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{-\hbar^{2}}{2m}\frac{\partial^{2}\psi}{\partial x^{2}}+V\psi=i\hbar\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial t}
\]

\end_inset

This equation holds for all functions of the potential, V, and not just
 for the free particle with potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 as was argued in the construction of the equation.
 This is a postulate that is agreed with by experimental data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SE is a complex second order differential equation and the solution, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x,t)$
\end_inset

 is generally also a complex function.
\end_layout

