\begin_layout Subsection
Probability Density Function (PDF)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $P(x,t)dx=$
\end_inset

probability of measuring the particle in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow x+dx$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(x,t)$
\end_inset

 must obey certain conditions.
 It must be
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
real
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
non-negative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
normalized so that 
\begin_inset Formula $P\geq1$
\end_inset

 does not occur.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In quantum mechanics,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(x,t) & = & |\psi|^{2}=\psi*\psi\\
\psi & = & a+ib\qquad\text{where }a,b\in\mathbb{R}\\
|\psi|^{2} & = & (a+ib)(a+ib)=a^{2}+b^{2}>0,\in\mathbb{R}\\
\therefore|\psi|^{2} & > & 0,\in\mathbb{R}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Normalization depends on the physical situation being described.
 The P over the whole of space must be =1 so that there is a 100% probability
 of measuring it somewhere.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Rightarrow\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}|\psi|^{2}dx=1
\]

\end_inset


\bar under
\noun on
Ex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(x,t)=\begin{cases}
A\cos(x)e^{-i\frac{Et}{\hbar}} & -\pi<x<\pi\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

[If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

is a solution of SE then so is 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=A\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

(the original wave-function multiplied by a constant)]
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\left(A\cos(x)e^{-i\frac{Et}{\hbar}}\right)\left(A\cos(x)e^{i\frac{Et}{\hbar}}\right)dx & = & 1\\
|A|^{2}\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\cos^{2}(x) & = & 1\\
|A|^{2}\frac{1}{2}\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}(1+\cos(2x))dx & = & 1\\
|A|^{2}\pi & = & 1\\
A & = & \frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}}\text{\:(Chosen A to be real)}\\
\Rightarrow\psi(x,t) & = & \begin{cases}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}}\cos(x)e^{\frac{-Et}{\hbar}} & -\pi<x<\pi\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

For a beam of particles, the normalization constant depends on the beam
 density.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Expectation Value
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quantum Mechanics cannot predict the outcome of a single measurement, it
 can only give a probability.
 We can calculate an average value over many repeated measurements.
 This is the expectation value.
 These repeated measurements must be of the exact same quantity so that
 the wave-function is identical.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
<x>=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}xP(x,t)dx
\]

\end_inset

This is simply the probability, P, weighted against the value of the displacemen
t, x.
 In quantum mechanics,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
<x>=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\psi*\psi dx
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $<x>$
\end_inset

 is the average, not a single measurement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
\noun on
Ex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\psi & = & A\cos(x)e^{\frac{-iEt}{\hbar}}\\
\Rightarrow<x> & = & \int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\left(A\cos(x)e^{\frac{-iEt}{\hbar}}\right)x\left(A\cos(x)e^{\frac{iEt}{\hbar}}\right)dx\\
 & = & A^{2}\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}x\cos^{2}(x)dx=0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\cos^{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 is an odd function and the integration is symmetric about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 This form is similar for other functions of x,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
<x> & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\psi*x^{2}\psi dx\\
<f(x)> & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\psi*f(x)\psi dx
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

However there are many quantities that might be needed, that cannot be written
 as functions of x, e.g the momentum, which would not be allowed by HUP if
 it dependent only on x.
 We can express these are mathematical operators,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{\mathcal{O}}f(x) & = & g(x)\\
\text{eg }\frac{d}{dx} & \left(x^{2}\right)= & 2x
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

In quantum mechanics, an operator extracts physical information from the
 wave-function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Momentum Operator:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{P}=-i\hbar\frac{\partial}{\partial x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
\noun on
Ex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Momentum of a free particle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=Ae^{i(kx-\omega t)}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{P}\psi & = & -i\hbar\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(Ae^{i(kx-\omega t)}\right)\\
 & = & -i\hbar ikAe^{i(kx-\omega t)}\\
 & = & \hbar kAe^{i(kx-\omega t)}\\
\Rightarrow\hat{P}\psi & = & \text{constant}*\psi\qquad\text{constant}=\hbar k
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Here the constant is equal to the momentum, 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\hbar k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Total Energy Operator:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{E}=i\hbar\frac{\partial}{\partial t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
\noun on
Ex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Total energy of a free particle,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E}\psi & = & i\hbar\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left(Ae^{i(kx-\omega t)}\right)\\
 & = & \hbar\omega Ae^{i(kx-\omega t)}\\
 & = & \hbar\omega\psi\\
\Rightarrow\hat{E}\psi & = & \text{constant}*\psi,\qquad\text{constant}=\hbar\omega
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Kinetic Energy Operator:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{E_{k}}=\hat{T} & = & \frac{\hat{P}^{2}}{2m}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2m}\left(-i\hbar\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\right)\left(-i\hbar\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\right)\\
 & = & -\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x^{2}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
\noun on
Ex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Kinetic energy of a free particle,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{\hat{P}^{2}}{2m}\psi & = & -\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\frac{\partial^{2}\psi}{\partial x^{2}}\\
 & = & -\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}(-k^{2})\psi=\frac{\hbar^{2}k^{2}}{2m}\psi\\
\Rightarrow\hat{E_{k}}\psi & = & \text{constant}*\psi\qquad\text{constant}=\frac{\hbar^{2}k^{2}}{2m}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

From these operators we can rewrite the Schrödinger Equation in a more compact
 form,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\frac{\partial^{2}\psi}{\partial x^{2}}+V\psi & = & i\hbar\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial t}\\
\frac{\hat{P}^{2}}{2m}\psi+V\psi & = & \hat{E}\psi\\
\mathcal{\hat{H}\psi} & = & \hat{E}\psi
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{\hat{H}}$
\end_inset

 is the Hamiltonian operator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A quantum mechanical operator extracts physical information form a wave-function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
e.g.
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=Ae^{i(kx-\omega t)}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}\psi=\hbar k\psi=p\psi$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\text{operator}\times(\text{function}) & = & \text{constant}\times(\text{function})\\
\hat{\mathcal{O}}\psi_{i} & = & a_{i}\psi_{i}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the eigenfunction of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathcal{O}}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the observable 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

, it represents a quantum eigenstate with a definite value for the observable
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
