\begin_layout Standard
We already know the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $V=0$
\end_inset

 and for 
\begin_inset Formula $V=V_{0}$
\end_inset

 separately as these are just TISE with a constant potential energy function.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\leq0,\; V=0,\;\psi_{1}(x)=Ae^{ik_{1}x}+Be^{-ik_{1}x}\qquad k_{1}=\frac{\sqrt{2mE}}{\hbar}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x>0,\; V=V_{0},\;\psi_{2}(x)=Ce^{ik_{2}x}+De^{-ik_{2}x}\qquad k_{2}=\frac{\sqrt{2m(E-V_{0})}}{\hbar}
\]

\end_inset

By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}<E$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{2}<k_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar k_{2}<\hbar k_{1}$
\end_inset

, which means the momentum after 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 is less than before so the particle slows down when it hits the potential
 barrier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Need physical boundary conditions to find A, B, C and D;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $De^{-ik_{2}x}$
\end_inset

 would represent a traveling reflected wave from the right hand side, though
 there is nothing to be reflected from, so can argue that this wave would
 not exist, so 
\begin_inset Formula $D=0,$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Rightarrow\psi_{2}=Ce^{ik_{2}x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Continuity considerations at boundary, 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

,
