\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\leq0,\; V=0,\;\psi_{1}(x)=Ae^{ik_{1}x}+Be^{-ik_{1}x}\qquad k_{1}=\frac{\sqrt{2mE}}{\hbar}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x>0,\; V=V_{0},\;\psi_{2}(x)=Ce^{-ik_{2}x}+De^{-ik_{2}x}\qquad k_{2}=\frac{\sqrt{2m(E-V_{0})}}{\hbar}
\]

\end_inset

This is identical to the situation where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}<E$
\end_inset

.
 Now however, when 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}>E$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{2}=\frac{\sqrt{2m\left(E-V_{0}\right)}}{\hbar}=a+ib
\]

\end_inset

.
 So the wavenumber is imaginary.
 So rewrite this as,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
k_{2} & = & \frac{-\sqrt{2m\left(V_{0}-E\right)}}{\hbar}\\
k_{2} & = & iK,\qquad\text{where }K=\frac{\sqrt{2m\left(V_{0}-E\right)}}{\hbar}\in\mathbb{R}>0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Rightarrow\psi_{2}(x)=Ce^{-Kx}+De^{Kx}
\]

\end_inset

Generally, the wave function of a particle is any region that is energetically
 forbidden has this real exponential form (not oscillatory).
 Use boundary conditions to determine the integration constants A, B, C
 and D.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{Kx}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
