\begin_layout Standard
The SHO is an important potential and is physically more realistic than
 the square well as it does not have any abrupt step in potential/ Classically,
 the simple harmonic oscillator is formed by displacing mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, by a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, from the equilibrium given there is a restoring force proportional to
 the displacement, 
\begin_inset Formula $-cx$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F & = & m\ddot{x}=-cx\\
\ddot{x} & = & -\frac{c}{m}x=-\omega^{2}x\qquad\omega=\sqrt{\frac{c}{m}}\text{ (angular frequency)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

In quantum mechanics, the force is linked to the displacement by,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F & = & -\frac{dV}{dx}=-cx\\
V & = & \int cxdx=\frac{1}{2}cx^{2}=\frac{1}{2}\omega^{2}x^{2}m
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This is a quadratic equation for the potential.
 So the shape of the simple harmonic oscillator is a parabolic well.
\end_layout

