\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A wave-function can be an eigenfunction of more that one operator, e.g.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi(x,t)=Ae^{i(kx-\omega t)}
\]

\end_inset

is an eigenfunction of momentum, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}=-i\hbar\frac{\partial}{\partial x}$
\end_inset

, with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\hbar k$
\end_inset

, and of energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}=i\hbar\frac{\partial}{\partial t}$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\hbar\omega$
\end_inset

.
 So we could know precisely the value of the momentum and the energy at
 the same time, without uncertainty.
 But some combinations of observables cannot be known simultaneously, e.g.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta x\Delta p\geq\frac{\hbar}{2}
\]

\end_inset

which is one form of the Heisenberg Uncertainty Principle.
 Commutation refers to the order in which operators or functions are acted.
 Most numbers, functions etc commute,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
2\times3 & = & 3\times2\\
xy & = & yx\\
 & \vdots
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

But in general, this is not true of operators, they don't all commute,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\frac{d}{dx}\psi\neq\frac{d}{dx}(x\psi)
\]

\end_inset

In general 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{A}\hat{B}\psi & \neq & \hat{B}\hat{A}\psi\\
\left(\hat{A}\hat{B}-\hat{B}\hat{A}\right)\psi & \neq & 0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


