\begin_layout Standard
This is another case of new phenomena that emerges when the higher dimensions
 are included, it cannot exist in 1D or 2D, it is an intrinsically 3D property.
 Classically,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{L}=\underline{r}\times\underline{p}\qquad\begin{cases}
\underline{L}_{x}=yp_{z}-zp_{y}\\
\underline{L}_{y}=zp_{x}-xp_{z}\\
\underline{L}_{z}=xp_{y}-yp_{x}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

So the quantum mechanical operator is a combination of the position and
 linear momentum operators,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{L}_{x} & = & -i\hbar\left(y\frac{\partial}{\partial z}-z\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\right)\\
\hat{L}_{y} & = & -i\hbar\left(z\frac{\partial}{\partial x}-x\frac{\partial}{\partial z}\right)\\
\hat{L}_{z} & = & -i\hbar\left(x\frac{\partial}{\partial y}-y\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

There also exists an operator for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\text{angular momentum}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{L}^{2}=\hat{L}_{x}^{2}+\hat{L}_{y}^{2}+\hat{L}_{z}^{2}
\]

\end_inset

So there are 4 quantum mechanical operators for the angular momentum of
 a particle in three dimensions.
 This starts from the premise that the position and the momentum are both
 known well, so that they can be combined to form the angular momentum.
 however this is expressly forbidden in quantum mechanics, due to the uncertaint
y product that relates them 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x\Delta p\geq\frac{\hbar}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Look at the operators and their commutation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{L}_{x},\hat{L}_{y}\right] & = & \hat{L}_{x}\hat{L}_{y}-\hat{L}_{y}\hat{L}_{x}\\
 & = & -\hbar^{2}\left[\left(y\frac{\partial}{\partial z}-z\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\right)\left(z\frac{\partial}{\partial x}-x\frac{\partial}{\partial z}\right)-\left(z\frac{\partial}{\partial x}-x\frac{\partial}{\partial z}\right)\left(y\frac{\partial}{\partial z}-z\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\right)\right]\\
 & = & -\hbar^{2}\left(y\frac{\partial}{\partial x}-x\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\right)\\
 & = & -\hbar^{2}\hat{L}_{z}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{L}_{x},\hat{L}_{y}\right] & = & -\hbar^{2}\hat{L}_{z}\\
\left[\hat{L}_{y},\hat{L}_{z}\right] & = & -\hbar^{2}\hat{L}_{x}\\
\left[\hat{L}_{z},\hat{L}_{x}\right] & = & -\hbar^{2}\hat{L}_{y}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So in general, the angular momentum operators do not commute, so we can
 know the precise value of only one component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{L}$
\end_inset

.
 We cannot know 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{L}=(L_{x},L_{y},L_{z})$
\end_inset

 fully.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analyze 
\begin_inset Formula $(\text{angular momentum})^{2}$
\end_inset

 operator.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\hat{L}^{2},\hat{L}_{z}\right]=\left[\hat{L}_{x}^{2},\hat{L}_{z}\right]+\left[\hat{L}_{y}^{2},\hat{L}_{z}\right]+\left[\hat{L}_{z}^{2},\hat{L}_{z}\right]
\]

\end_inset

Since any operator always commutes with itself,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{L}_{z}^{2},\hat{L}_{z}\right] & = & 0\\
\left[\hat{L}_{x}^{2},\hat{L}_{z}\right] & = & \left[\hat{L}_{x}\hat{L}_{x},\hat{L}_{z}\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Use commutator identity mentioned previously,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\hat{A}\hat{B},\hat{C}\right]=\hat{A}\left[\hat{B},\hat{C}\right]+\left[\hat{A},\hat{C}\right]\hat{B}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Rightarrow\left[\hat{L}_{x}^{2},\hat{L}_{z}\right] & = & \hat{L_{x}}\left[\hat{L_{x}},\hat{L_{z}}\right]+\left[\hat{L_{x}},\hat{L_{z}}\right]\hat{L_{x}}\\
 & = & \hat{L_{x}}\left(-i\hbar\hat{L_{y}}\right)+\left(-i\hbar\hat{L_{y}}\right)\hat{L_{x}}\\
 & = & -i\hbar\left(\hat{L}_{x}\hat{L}_{y}-\hat{L}_{y}\hat{L}_{x}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Similarly
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{L}_{y}^{2},\hat{L}_{z}\right] & = & i\hbar\left(\hat{L}_{y}\hat{L}_{x}-\hat{L}_{x}\hat{L}_{y}\right)\\
\Rightarrow\left[\hat{L}_{x}^{2},\hat{L}_{z}\right] & = & -\left[\hat{L}_{y}^{2},\hat{L}_{z}\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\hat{L}^{2},\hat{L}_{z}\right]=0+0=0
\]

\end_inset

Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\hat{L}^{2},\hat{L}_{z}\right] & = & \left[\hat{L}^{2},\hat{L}_{y}\right]=0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\text{angular momentum}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 commutes with all three components of the angular momentum separately.
 Therefore we can know the precise value of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\text{angular momentum}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 
\noun on
and 
\noun default
one component only of angular momentum simultaneously.
 By convention, we chose to know the z component, along with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, we can know the magnitude of the angular momentum, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\underline{L}|=\sqrt{L^{2}}$
\end_inset

, but not the direction of this magnitude.
\end_layout

