\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu=\frac{mM}{m+M}
\]

\end_inset

This is the same as the classical situation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Single Electron Atoms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Coulomb potential causes an attraction between the electron and the nucleus,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(\underline{r})=\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}r}\qquad F(\underline{r})=\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}r^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=Ze$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is the atomic number, 1 for hydrogen) and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}=-e$
\end_inset

.
 This coulomb potential is an example of a radial or central potential as
 it depends only on the separation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(\underline{r})=V(r)
\]

\end_inset

so it is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
TISE for an electron on an atom, therefore, is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\nabla^{2}-\frac{Ze^{2}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}r}\right)\psi(r,\theta,\phi)=E\psi(r,\theta,\phi)
\]

\end_inset

For the specific hydrogen atom case, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 would equal 1.
 The Laplacian operator in spherical polar co-ordinates is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla^{2}=\frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left(r^{2}\frac{\partial}{\partial r}\right)+\frac{1}{r^{2}\sin(\theta)}\frac{\partial}{\partial\theta}\left(\sin(\theta)\frac{\partial}{\partial\theta}\right)+\frac{1}{r^{2}\sin^{2}(\theta)}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial\phi^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

Though this equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}$
\end_inset

 is more complicated than for Cartesian co-ordinates, this form allows the
 equation to be solved by separation of variables.
 Something that is not possible when in Cartesian.
 Using this method, the result is that eigenfunctions are found with the
 form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(r,\theta,\phi)=R(r)Y(\theta,\phi)
\]

\end_inset

which is composed of a radial part and an angular part.
 Th solution of TISE also gives values for the energy eigenvalues.
 These are a set of distinct energy eigenvalues of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E_{n} & = & \frac{-\mu Z^{2}e^{4}}{\left(4\pi\epsilon_{0}\right)^{2}2\hbar^{2}n^{2}}\\
E_{n} & \propto & -\frac{1}{n^{2}}\qquad n\in\mathbb{Z}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So the electron is bound to the nucleus with discrete quantized energy levels
 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}\propto-\frac{1}{n^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=1$
\end_inset

 (hydrogen atom),
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{n}=\frac{-13.6\unit{eV}}{n^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}$
\end_inset

 is negative because the potential is defined to be 
\begin_inset Formula $V=0$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\infty$
\end_inset

, so any value of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 less than 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 will produce a value of potential that is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 There exists an infinite number of bound states but the energy separation
 tends to zero as 
\begin_inset Formula $r\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $E=13.6\unit{eV}$
\end_inset

 is the ionization energy for the electron in the ground state of the hydrogen
 atom.
\end_layout

