\begin_layout Section
Atomic Quantum Numbers and Polar Co-ordinates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most important quantum number is the one used here, called 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the principle quantum number (sometimes also called the radial quantum
 number or the shell quantum number).
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 alone determines the energy level 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}\propto-\frac{1}{n^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 All eigenstates of the electron within the atom with the same 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 quantum number vale have the same value.
 This is because of the energy degeneracy, and arises due to the very symmetrica
l system in which the electrons are confined, ie a spherical potential,
 
\begin_inset Formula $V(r)$
\end_inset

.
 The radius (or , 
\begin_inset Formula $<r>$
\end_inset

) of the atom increases along with the energy as the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 value increases.
 The solution of TISE also restricts the angular momentum quantum number
 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
l<n\qquad(l\neq n)
\]

\end_inset

so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\leq l<n
\]

\end_inset

So for the three atomic quantum numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $n,l,m$
\end_inset

 are all integers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $n>0$
\end_inset

, determines the energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}\propto-\frac{1}{n^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and the radius
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq l<n$
\end_inset

, determines the magnitude of the orbital angular momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $|L|=\sqrt{l\left(l+1\right)\hbar^{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $-l\leq m_{l}\leq l$
\end_inset

, determines the component of the orbital angular momentum about the z-axis
 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{z}=m_{R}\hbar$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Set 
\begin_inset Formula $n,l,m_{l}$
\end_inset

 as the labels for the electron eigenstates in the atom.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(r,\theta,\phi)=R_{n,l}(r)Y_{l,m}(\theta,\phi)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $R_{n,l}(r)$
\end_inset

 is the radial component that depends on the principle quantum number, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and the angular momentum quantum number, 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

, and is a function only of the radial distance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{l,m}(\theta,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is the angular component that depends on the angular momentum quantum number
 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 number and is a function of the angles 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Radial Wave-function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This depends on the quantum numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{n,l}(r)=e^{-\frac{Zr}{na_{0}}}\left(\frac{Zr}{a_{0}}\right)^{l}G_{n,l}\left(\frac{Zr}{a_{0}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=\frac{4\pi\epsilon_{0}\hbar}{\mu e^{2}}\approx0.529\times10^{-10}\unit{m}\approx\frac{\text{Å}}{2}$
\end_inset

 this is referred to as the Bohr radius, and is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

radius
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of a ground state hydrogen atom.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $G_{n,l}\left(\frac{Zr}{a_{0}}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial function of the order 
\begin_inset Formula $n-(l+1)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-\frac{Zr}{na_{0}}}$
\end_inset

 tends to zero as r increases to infinity since 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is on the denominator of the exponential.
 This means as the energy levels increase, ie 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 increases, the average radius increases as the exponential penetrates further
 into the potential wall.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first few unnormalized states are given by,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
R_{1,0} & \propto & e^{-\frac{Zr}{a_{0}}}\\
R_{2,0} & \propto & \left(1-\frac{Zr}{2a_{0}}\right)e^{-\frac{Zr}{2a_{0}}}\\
R_{2,1} & \propto & \frac{Zr}{a_{0}}e^{-\frac{Zr}{2a_{0}}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Hence we can evaluate the radial probability density functions,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(r)dr=|R_{nl}|^{2}\times4\pi r^{2}dr
\]

\end_inset

The final term comes from the area of the sphere,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{2\pi}rd\phi\int_{0}^{\pi}r\sin\theta d\theta dr
\]

\end_inset


