\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mu & = & \text{current}\times\text{area}\\
 & = & \frac{-e}{\left(\frac{2\pi r}{v}\right)}\times\pi r^{2}\\
 & = & \frac{-ver}{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Also, the angular momentum, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\underline{L} & = & \underline{r}\times\underline{p}\\
|\underline{L}| & = & rmv\\
\Rightarrow\mu & = & -\frac{eL}{2m}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This is for, for example, an electron orbiting around a nucleus.
 Rewrite this as,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{\mu_{l}}=-\frac{g_{l}\mu_{B}}{\hbar}\underline{L}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 denotes the orbital angular momentum, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{B}=\frac{e\hbar}{2m}=0.927\times10^{-23}\unit[A]{m^{2}}$
\end_inset

(this is the Bohr magneton and is the typical unit used for the magnetic
 dipole moment of an atom), 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{l}=1$
\end_inset

 (this is the orbital 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 factor for consistency with equation later on).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This was a purely classical electromagnetic argument, but the quantum mechanical
 analysis gives the same equation.
 In quantum mechanics, we can know the precise values of the magnitude and
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 component of the dipole moment.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\text{Magnitude}\qquad|\mu_{l}| & = & \frac{g_{l}\mu_{B}}{\hbar}\sqrt{l(l+1)}\hbar\\
 & = & g_{l}\mu_{B}\sqrt{l(l+1)}\\
z\text{ component}\qquad(\mu_{l})_{z} & = & -\frac{g_{l}\mu_{B}}{\hbar}m_{l}\hbar\\
 & = & -g_{l}\mu_{B}m_{l}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

To measure the magnetic dipole, a non-uniform magnetic field is needed.
\end_layout

