\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Predicted Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For classical (unquantified) system, the angular momentum would be expected
 to be continuous with a range of 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{z}$
\end_inset

 values,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-L\leq L_{z}\leq L
\]

\end_inset

This would give a range of all possible results when measured, so a stripe
 would be seen on the screen.
 For the quantized quantum mechanical system, there are only certain discrete
 values of 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{z}$
\end_inset

, e.g.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $L=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{z}=-\hbar,\,0,\,\hbar$
\end_inset

 so there would exist only three different spots on the screen from these
 possible values of the angular momentum.
 Generally there are 
\begin_inset Formula $2l+1$
\end_inset

 values of 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{l}$
\end_inset

 so the expected number of spots to be seen would be 
\begin_inset Formula $2l+1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 is an integer, and odd number of spots should be seen.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Measured Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the simplest case of a hydrogen atom in it's ground state energy
 level, so 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $l=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{l}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{z}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Expected results would be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{z}=0$
\end_inset

 so no deflections and only one spot.
 But this is not what was measured.
 The result observed was 
\emph on
two
\emph default
 spots with an equal deflection in the positive and negative directions
 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{z}=\pm\mu_{B}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

