\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Bosons
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bosons are particles with integer spin, 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0,1,2,3\ldots$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, e.g.
 photon, pion, 
\begin_inset Formula $^{4}\text{He}$
\end_inset

 nucleus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{W}^{\pm}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Z}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Importantly, for bosons, an unlimited number of them can occupy the same
 quantum state simultaneously.
 This leads to important phenomena like lasers, super-conductivity, super-fluidi
ty, Bose-Einstein condensates etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Fermions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fermions are half integer spin particles, 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\frac{1}{2},\frac{3}{2},\frac{5}{2}\ldots$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\frac{\mathbb{Z}}{2}$
\end_inset

, e.g.
 electron, proton, quark, 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}\text{He}$
\end_inset

 nucleus etc.
 The Pauli exclusion principle states that no two fermions can occupy the
 same quantum state simultaneously.
 Alternatively, no two fermions can share exactly the same set of quantum
 numbers.
 This is essential for multi-electron atoms as it means the electrons cannot
 all occupy the ground state, and so leads to the field of chemistry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Atomic Quantum Numbers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now need 4 quantum numbers to specify the eigenstate of the electron,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n,l,m_{l},m_{s}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $m_{s}=\pm\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

, gives the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-component of the spin angular momentum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternative set of 4 quantum numbers,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n,l,j,m_{j}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $j,m_{j}$
\end_inset

 give the magnitude and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-component of the total angular momentum.
 The first set is fine for single electron atoms, but this leads to ambiguity
 when multi-electrons are considered.
 So the second set is used to reduce ambiguity and simplify definitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Multi-Electron Atoms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Pauli Exclusion Principle requires that, when more than one electron
 is present, they occupy different eigenstates.
 For the ground state atom, the lowest states are occupied first, that is,
 the lowest 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-value and lowest 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

-value are filled first.
 As more eigenstates are filled, the different elements with different chemical
 properties are formed.
\end_layout

