\begin_layout Standard
Atomic electrons can transition between one state and another, emitting
 or absorbing a photon of energy equal to the difference between the energy
 levels.
 This is the field of spectroscopy.
 Only certain transitions are allowed, obeying certain selection rules:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l$
\end_inset

 must be 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

 
\noun on
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta j$
\end_inset

 must be 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These rules arise from the photon properties and conservation laws,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta j=0,\pm1$
\end_inset

 because a photon is a spin 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1$
\end_inset

 particle, so carries a unit angular momentum, so to conserve angular momentum,
 the atom must change by one unit.
 So either 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta j=\pm1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}$
\end_inset

 changes by one unit, eg 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}=-\frac{1}{2}\leftrightarrow m_{j}=+\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

, this is when the spin flips.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l=\pm1$
\end_inset

 comes from the property of parity.
 The photon has a negative intrinsic parity which must be conserved.
 So when the photon is emitted or absorbed, the parity of the atom must
 change.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Atomic parity}=(-1)^{l}$
\end_inset

 (from symmetry of angular wave-function, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{l,m}$
\end_inset

) So 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l=\pm1$
\end_inset

 changes parity.
\end_layout

